nt of   Twyford  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor Twyford was born in 1321, in Kedleston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Robert Twyford, was 26 and her mother, Elizabeth Braylesford, was 25. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with John Curzon Snr. She died in 1380, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1321–1380":"1321–1380","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1785–1787":"1785–1787","–Female":"Surnud","1315–1406":"1315–1406","1339–1462":"1339–1462","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1377–Female":"1377–Surnud","1295–1345":"1295–1345","1296–Female"